<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="keywords" content="Met Office" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Memo</title></head><body style="background:#ffffff"><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Written evidence from the Met Office (WRT 003)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What lessons have been learned since the severe weather experienced in the winter of 2009-10? What practical changes have been made to ensure the UK is now better equipped to deal with severe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">weather?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">High resolution forecasting: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Forecasting extreme winter events can be very challenging. Increased resolution the Met Office’s forecast model means small-scale events that cause severe impacts are now better profiled at increased lead ti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Impacts based warnings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The National Severe Weather Warning Service was improved following consultation with the emergency response community and now reflects the impacts of severe weather in a simple and easy to read format.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Communication and reach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> Met Office has embraced social media and improved mobile app technology to ensure our forecasts and warning are more accessible and immediate to all users.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Seasonal forecast</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ing: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We are seeing some improvement in seasonal forecasting skill following t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">he recent upgrade to the GloSea5 model. With improved skill and increased understanding of user needs the Met Office is committed to making this important planning aid truly complementary to its short term operational services. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Collaboration and partnersh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ips</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Met Office has increased it collaborative and partnering work with users, other environmental service providers and with Government to maximise the value of its forecasts and warnings and to drive improvements in our science and services.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">High </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Performance Computing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">: HPC is a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> critical underpinning component of the Met Office’s capability in weather forecasting and climate research. The Government’s commitment, announced in the 2013 spending review, to invest in a new super computer will deliver w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ide-ranging socio-economic benefits including in the transport and resilience areas.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Met Office is the UK’s National Weather Service and provides a range of services to the public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">through an increasing number of channels to help them ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ke informed decisions about their day-to-day activities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">he National Severe Weather Warning Service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">(NSWWS) is a key aspect of this public service and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> advance warning of extreme weather to the public, businesses, emergency services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">, infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> operators including in road, rail and aviation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> and Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">in order to mitigate its impacts and resulting disruption and help protect lives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">livelihoods, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">property and infrastructure.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Accurate weather forecasts and timely warnings are a critical compone</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">nt in ensuring winter resilience across the transport sector. Severe weather warnings provide the precise detail of severe events and, with a contextual understanding of the impacts, allow local resilience forums to mobilise and prepare and the public are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">able to make informed decisions and take appropriate action.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">onthly and operational 5-day forecasts allow better resource- and area-specific planning as well as providing increasingly early indication of the potential for severe events.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Seasonal and month</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ly forecasts provide the capacity for increased planning on the longer and broader scale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">In early 2011 the Transport Select Committee held an inquiry on the impacts on transport of the adverse weather experienced across the UK during December 2010. The M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">et Office provided written evidence at that time summarising the conditions experienced, the challenges these presented in terms of weather forecasting, severe weather warnings and communication, the lessons learned and our commitment to continued improvem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ent in these key areas.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">We are pleased to update the Committee on our progress </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">in this important area </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">since the 2011 report.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">igh resolution forecasting</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Forecasting severe and extreme winter events can be very challenging – particularly when events are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">local in scale. Predicting snowfall rates and accumulations is particularly difficult, because often the difference between rain and snow is very marginal in terms of atmospheric conditions but very large in terms of impact.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Since the last Committee inquir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">y the Met Office has made good progress in implementing high-resolution forecast models. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">he Met Office's UK forecast model now has a higher resolution with increased geographical detail allowing significant improvements in the specific profile of local e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">vents. High resolution model forecasts, combined with the expert knowledge of a dedicated forecast team, means not only can events be better pinpointed but the lead time is increased and the nuances of specific terrain is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> better</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> understood. Improved detail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">, in terms of both profile and location of severe events, and increased lead time means the NSWWS provides even greater benefit in terms of saving lives and livelihoods through aiding preparation and recovery. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">This is particularly important for forecasting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> those small scale convective events so often associated with severe weather, such as the Boscastle flood in 2004 or hail storm of Ottery St Mary in 2008, that although localised often cause severe impacts.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Impacts based warnings</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">At the time of the last in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">quiry the Met Office launched a new imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">act based warning service following extensive consultation with the emergency response community. Rather than issue warnings simply based on meteorological thresholds, the Met Office worked closely with responders to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">better understand how different weather events affected their decision-making. The result of this collaborative approach has been a system of warnings that is triggered on the basis of likely impact on the ground. We know that an inch of snow in some parts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> of the country has a bigger impact than 3 inches of snow somewhere else and it is sensible to reflect this in our warnings system. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Met Office issues warnings for rain, fog, wind, snow and ice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which are colour coded from yellow to amber to red </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">depend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ing on a combination of both the likelihood of the event happening and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">, after detailed discussion with emergency responders,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> the impact the conditions may have.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The warnings are issued on the Met Office web site overlaid on a map of the UK allowing users t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">o see at a glance the areas affected and to what level of impact.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Nine workshops with the emergency response communities, including local resilience forums, were held across the UK during summer 2013 to gather feedback on the changes so far and discuss fut</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ure avenues for improvement. Levels of understanding of the warnings and satisfaction with accuracy were found to be high.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Communication and reach</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Alongside timeliness and accuracy, a single authoritative voice remains critical in times of severe weather e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">vents in order to drive timely action. Direct dialogue with the emergency response community has long been recognised as important in this respect. The 15 strong-team of Met Office Advisors works closely with local resilience forums, and indeed on occasion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> with other community groups, to understand the specific resilience issues for each distinct event thereby allowing the forecasts and warnings to be fully contextualised. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">E</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">volving and complex situations require expert and immediate interpretation</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Met Office has, in addition to the regional advisors, embedded forecasters within the Highways Agency and on request at DfT who maintain a dedicated desk for Met Office staff. This coming winter we will again have a forecaster on site working directly alon</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">gside the Highways Agency and within Transport Scotland. There will also be a forecast team on site at Heathrow until March 2014</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Met Office also continues to provide direct and continual updates during severe events to central Government and Officials including DfT and CCS and to the devolved administrations. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 35.5pt; padding-left:0.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Met Office has also improved its direct reach to the public who n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ow have various routes through which to access forecasts and warnings. The BBC remains a key delivery partner providing national and regional reach and local details are available through our improved website, mobile apps and a newly launched severe weathe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">r widget that is freely available for businesses to host on their own websites.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> In additional social media channels such as Twitter, where we have in the region of 145,000 followers, provide an unprecedented reach through which to keep the public updated i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">n real time. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Seasonal forecast</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ing</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">A key aspect of winter resilience is forward planning. Seasonal forecasts, already providing increasing benefits in some areas of the world, remain challenging for UK. The Met Office is confident, however, that some poten</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">tially significant improvements are expected following the recent launch of the Met Office's Global Seasonal Forecast System (GloSea5). This model is a significant upgrade providing much increased resolution. Preliminary analysis of testing performance for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> the last few decades shows some improvement in skill.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Met Office's continued efforts in driving forecasting on the seasonal scale is being welcomed within a number of Government Departments and Agencies, including DfT, and particularly for winter plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ning. The Met Office had previously provided paper briefs for the 3-month period ahead to Government but  ahead of winter 2012/13 the senior scientist leading this work complemented this routine publication by providing a personal and in-depth briefing. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">is exercise provided significant improvement in understanding of the usefulness of the seasonal forecast and, importantly, its limitations and areas of uncertainty. The briefing also provided vital feedback to the Met Office on the fundamental needs of use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">rs of this type of planning aid. A seasonal briefing is again scheduled to take place in late November for the winter 2013/14 season. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">In addition, and taking forward the lessons from the national brief, the Met Office is now beginning to explore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">how this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">type of forecast can be more regionalised to benefit agencies with a sub-national remit.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> With increased understanding and much improved skill, the Met Office is committed to ensuring seasonal forecasts develop to become truly complementary to the short ter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">m operational forecasts and warnings which already perform a crucial role in helping the UK manage its vulnerabilities to and risk from severe weather.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Collaboration and partnerships</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Met Office plays an important role in winter resilience, but in order</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> to maximise the value of what we do it is essential that we work in partnership with others. In this respect, the Met Office has worked hard to ensure we are better connected with all Government Departments in order to fully understand their needs and dem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">onstrate how our science can help them discharge their responsibilities.  A strong relationship exists between the DfT and the Met Office, built up over a number of years through working with agencies including the Highways Agency, Civil Aviation Authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Marine and Coastguard Agency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">. In October 2012 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">a high level Memorandum of Understanding was signed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">between the DfT and Met Office </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">which lays out general principles of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">working together and is designed to make it easier on both sides to facilitate Me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">t Office working with DfT in the future.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">   </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">At the operational level, collaboration with other environmental service providers has already shown great benefit in the form of the Flood Forecast Centre (FFC) where meteorological and hydrological expertise is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> combined. Since its establishment in 2009, the FFC has gone from strength to strength and there is a growing body of evidence that it has played a significant role in reducing the impact and financial cost of flooding events. The Environment Agency estima</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">tes that approximately £236m of flood damage costs are avoided through its flood warning service in England and Wales. Working in collaboration, the Met Office plays a key enabling role in enhancing these benefits by providing accurate and timely weather f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">orecasts and warnings. A similar partnership between the Met Office and SEPA operates in Scotland. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Met Office led Natural Hazard Partnership (NHP) is a wider collaboration across the UK's public sector environmental expertise with the aim of enabling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">an even more coordinated and coherent advice base for the Government and resilience communities. Following in the success of the FFC the NHP is also maturing as the 12 partners work together with 5 Government Agencies on the development of hazard impact mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">dels.  These models will look to scientifically combine likely hazard severity with an assessment of underpinning vulnerability and population/asset exposure to the hazard.  Currently, prototype strong wind vehicle over-turning, landslide and surface water</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> flooding models are being trialled with some early successes already evidenced by the  first ever landslide hazard advice being issued for south-west England, issued jointly by the Met Office and British Geological Survey during the heavy rain events of D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">ecember 2012.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">High Performance Computing</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The Committee’s report of 2011 recognised that H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">igh </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">erformance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">omputing (HPC)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> is a critical underpinning component of the Met Office’s capability in weather forecasting and climate research, both of which have an important role to play in winter resilience. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">The investment received from DECC and Defra following the last inquiry has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt"> enabled the Met Office to accelerate the implementation of high-resolution, probabilistic forecast models that have strengthened our ability to predict local-scale weather events. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Since that time there has been further support from Government for high pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">rformance computing, with the recent announcement of a new supercomputer for the Met Office as part of the capital spending round for 2015/16. The details of the investment are being finalised, but such a step change in investment would deliver wide-rangin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">g socio-economic benefits across a number of sectors, including transport and resilience. We will keep the Committee informed of developments, as appropriate. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The ongoing service provider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is expected to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">be announced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in early 2014 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">at the conclusion of an open commercial tender. The Met Office has responded.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>